## Semantic Tokens

The theme system manages colors through semantic tokens rather than direct hex values. This approach makes dark mode transitions seamless.

| Token | Description | Light | Dark |
|-------|-------------|-------|------|
| `bg.primary` | Main background | `#ffffff` | `#0f172a` |
| `bg.secondary` | Secondary background | `#f8fafc` | `#1e293b` |
| `text.primary` | Main text color | `#0f172a` | `#f8fafc` |
| `text.secondary` | Secondary text | `#64748b` | `#94a3b8` |
| `border.default` | Default border | `#e2e8f0` | `#334155` |
| `interactive.primary` | Primary interaction | `#3b82f6` | `#60a5fa` |

## CSS Custom Properties

All tokens are also accessible as CSS custom properties:

```css
.my-component {
  color: var(--mfe-text-primary);
  background: var(--mfe-bg-primary);
  border: 1px solid var(--mfe-border-default);
  padding: var(--mfe-spacing-4);
}
```

## Theme Extension

You can partially override the existing theme — only specify the tokens you want to change:

```tsx
<DesignSystemProvider
  theme={{
    colors: {
      primary: { 500: '#8b5cf6' },  // only primary.500 changes
    },
  }}
>
  <YourApp />
</DesignSystemProvider>
```

<Aside type="caution">
  Avoid hardcoding theme tokens directly in CSS. Use semantic tokens to maintain dark mode and high-contrast compatibility.
</Aside>

